tions in the semiotics of everyday life.Drawing on a set of thirty-three research interviews focused on disabled faculty members' experiences with disability disclosure, as well as written narratives by disabled people, this book argues for the materiality of narrative, suggesting narratives as a means by which people enact boundaries around phenomena and determine their properties. Signs of Disability offers strategies and practices for challenging problematic and pervasive forms of "dis-attention" and proposes a new theoretical model for understanding disability in social, rhetorical, and material settings.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aThis eBook is made available Open Access under a CC BY-NC-ND 4.0 license: uhttps://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-nd/4.0  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aPeople with disabilities. 0aSociology of disability. 7aHEALTH & FITNESS / Hearing & Speech.2bisacsh  aAccessibility.  aAsia Friedman.  aDeafness.  aDisability and architecture.  aDisability.  aEntextualization.  aKaren Barad.  aMateriality.  aRhetoric.  aTherí Pickens.  aagential realism.  abooks about disability and Accessibility.  aclosed captioning.  adisability and deafness.  adisability and praxis.  adisability and storytelling.  adisability studies.  adisabled practices.  aembodiment.  ahearing aids.  aintra-action.  amaterial environment and disability.  amaterialist approach.  aperceiving disability.  arhetoric and disability.  asensory perception and disability.40uhttps://doi.org/10.18574/nyu/9781479811182.001.0001zOpen Access7040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781479811182zOpen Access70423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781479811182/original  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aZDB-23-GOA